LOCATION:SIDNEY AND LOIS ESKENAZI MUSEUM OF ART
GEO:39.169144;-86.519739
SUMMARY:Curator-led Tour and Reception
DESCRIPTION:3:30 - 4:00 p.m. | Curator-led Tour | Featured Exhibitions Ga
 llery&#160\;  Join us for a rare opportunity to explore the exhibition wi
 th Tasha Kimmet\, Curator of Asian Art.&#160\; This is a guided tour that
  starts at 3:30 p.m. If you miss the tour\, you're welcome to drop in to 
 explore the exhibition at your own pace until 5 p.m.&#160\;&#160\;4 - 5 p
 .m. | Reception | Martin Commons  After the tour\, drop by the Martin Com
 mons (2nd floor) for a light reception to celebrate this exhibition with 
 the Asian Culture Center and Asian Pacific American Faculty and Staff Cou
 ncil.About the Exhibition  Inspired by Indonesia's spectacular coral reef
 s\, acclaimed fiber artist Mulyana (b. 1984\, Bandung\, Indonesia) has cr
 eated an immersive\, handcrafted seascape where art and ecology meet. Exp
 lore colorful coral reefs\, playful fish\, and fantastical sea creatures 
 ŌĆö all meticulously hand-knit and crocheted ŌĆö while learning about how
  human wellness is interconnected with the wellbeing of our oceans.&#160\
 ;Acknowledgement  This program is hosted jointly by IU Asian Culture Cent
 er\, Asian Pacific American Faculty and Staff Council\, and the Eskenazi 
 Museum of Art.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><strong>3:30 - 4:00 p.m. | Curator-led To
 ur | Featured Exhibitions Gallery&#160\;</strong></p><p>  Join us for a r
 are opportunity to explore the exhibition with Tasha Kimmet\, Curator of 
 Asian Art.&#160\; This is a guided tour that starts at 3:30 p.m. If you m
 iss the tour\, you're welcome to drop in to explore the exhibition at you
 r own pace until 5 p.m.&#160\;&#160\;</p><p><strong>4 - 5 p.m. | Receptio
 n | Martin Commons</strong></p><p>  After the tour\, drop by the Martin C
 ommons (2nd floor) for a light reception to celebrate this exhibition wit
 h the Asian Culture Center and <span data-olk-copy-source="MessageBody">A
 sian Pacific American Faculty and Staff Council.</span></p><p><strong>Abo
 ut the Exhibition</strong></p><p>  Inspired by Indonesia's spectacular co
 ral reefs\, acclaimed fiber artist Mulyana (b. 1984\, Bandung\, Indonesia
 ) has created an immersive\, handcrafted seascape where art and ecology m
 eet. Explore colorful coral reefs\, playful fish\, and fantastical sea cr
 eatures ŌĆö all meticulously hand-knit and crocheted ŌĆö while learning a
 bout how human wellness is interconnected with the wellbeing of our ocean
 s.&#160\;</p><p><strong>Acknowledgement</strong></p><p>  This program is 
 hosted jointly by <span data-olk-copy-source="MessageBody">IU Asian Cultu
 re Center\, Asian Pacific American Faculty and Staff Council\, and the Es
 kenazi Museum of Art.</span></p>
